I want to make several architectural improvements to index.html. I've diagnosed each issue — please make these specific fixes without touching anything else (no CSS changes, no HTML changes, no rewrites of unrelated code).

FIX 1: Remove the failsafe setInterval.
It was a bandaid for a bug that's now properly fixed. Delete this entire block:

// Failsafe: if URL has no hash but feed is not visible, force it
setInterval(() => {
  if (!window.location.hash && feedPage.classList.contains('hidden')) {
    showFeed(0);
  }
}, 300);

FIX 2: Store scroll position on history state instead of a shared variable.
Currently savedScrollY is a module-level variable that gets clobbered when opening a second article, so browser back/forward restores the wrong scroll position. Instead:
- In openArticle, pass the scrollY into pushState's state object (it's already being done) but stop relying on the savedScrollY variable for restoration.
- In the popstate handler, read scrollY from event.state when available.
- Keep savedScrollY as a fallback only for the direct closeArticle() button path.

Update the popstate handler to:

window.addEventListener('popstate', (e) => {
  var hash = window.location.hash.slice(1);
  var restoreY = (e.state && typeof e.state.scrollY === 'number') ? e.state.scrollY : 0;
  if (!hash) {
    // Returning to feed — use the state's scrollY if present
    if (current) {
      // Coming back from an article via browser back
      document.querySelectorAll('.article').forEach(a => a.classList.remove('in', 'entering'));
      document.querySelectorAll('.feed-item.stream-open').forEach(el => el.classList.remove('stream-open'));
      feedPage.classList.remove('hidden', 'out');
      feedPage.style.removeProperty('display');
      feedPage.style.removeProperty('opacity');
      ['.feed', '.home-footer'].forEach(sel => {
        const el = feedPage.querySelector(sel);
        if (!el) return;
        el.style.animation = 'none';
        void el.offsetWidth;
        el.style.animation = '';
      });
      current = null;
      window.scrollTo(0, restoreY);
    }
  } else if (articles[hash] && !current) {
    _showArticle(hash);
  }
});

FIX 3: Separate the visual work of opening an article from the history push.
Currently popstate calls openArticle, which calls history.pushState, which pollutes the history stack when navigating via forward button. Extract a new internal function _showArticle(id) that does all the visual work (adding classes, initMurmur, changelog word count, scroll to 0) WITHOUT calling pushState. Then openArticle becomes a thin wrapper that calls _showArticle(id) and then calls history.pushState.

Structure:

function _showArticle(id) {
  current = id;
  feedPage.classList.add('out');
  setTimeout(() => {
    feedPage.classList.add('hidden');
    const article = articles[id];
    article.classList.add('entering');
    if (id === 'murmur') initMurmur();
    void article.offsetHeight;
    article.classList.add('in');
    window.scrollTo(0, 0);
    if (id === 'changelog') {
      const content = document.getElementById('changelogContent');
      const el = document.getElementById('changelogWordCount');
      if (content && el) {
        const words = content.textContent.trim().split(/\s+/).filter(w => w.length > 0).length;
        el.textContent = words.toLocaleString();
      }
    }
  }, 350);
}

function openArticle(id) {
  if (current) return;
  savedScrollY = window.scrollY;
  _showArticle(id);
  history.pushState({ article: id, scrollY: savedScrollY }, '', '#' + id);
}

FIX 4: Deduplicate the initial hash-on-load logic.
The block that runs at the bottom of the script (starting with `if (window.location.hash)`) manually replicates what openArticle does. Replace it with a version that uses the same code path. Since on initial load we want the article visible immediately without the 350ms transition, use this:

if (window.location.hash) {
  const id = window.location.hash.slice(1);
  if (articles[id]) {
    feedPage.classList.add('out', 'hidden');
    articles[id].classList.add('entering', 'in');
    current = id;
    if (id === 'murmur') initMurmur();
    if (id === 'changelog') {
      const content = document.getElementById('changelogContent');
      const el = document.getElementById('changelogWordCount');
      if (content && el) {
        const words = content.textContent.trim().split(/\s+/).filter(w => w.length > 0).length;
        el.textContent = words.toLocaleString();
      }
    }
  }
}

Actually leave this as-is — it needs to skip the transition. The dedup isn't worth the complexity here.

FIX 5: Add `void` to the reflow trick in _showArticle.
The existing code has `article.offsetHeight;` on its own line as a reflow trigger. Change it to `void article.offsetHeight;` so the intent is explicit and minifiers don't strip it.

FIX 6: Change html { font-size: 16px } to html { font-size: 100%; } for accessibility — this respects user browser font-size preferences.

