I'm adding a sandbox artifact from one of my projects (Prompting People — a writing app where one prompt goes live at a time and people respond) to my
  portfolio. It's a recreation of the "journal entry" component from that app, frozen in display state with a typeable textarea where the body would be.
  It's a portfolio piece, not a live integration — nothing saves, nothing fetches.

  Where it should live

  On the work page, beneath the description of Prompting People. Find the section/block on the work page that describes Prompting People and place the
  component directly below that description. Look at the existing layout rhythm of that page and pick a width/wrapper treatment that fits — the component
  is self-contained at min(56vh, 480px) tall and stretches to fill its container's width, so a sensible max-width container (the same one used for
  surrounding text blocks is probably fine) will work.

  Constraints — please respect these

  - This portfolio is Next.js 16 App Router with plain CSS. No Tailwind, no PostCSS, no design-token system. Styling lives in app/v2.css and
  app/globals.css using raw CSS custom properties (--v2-bg, --v2-ink, --v2-accent, etc.) on the .site-v2 scope.
  - Do not introduce Tailwind, CSS-in-JS libraries, or any new build tooling. The component below is intentionally self-contained: all its styles live in
  an inline <style> block inside the component file, scoped via .rjs-* class names so they won't collide with the existing .v2-* system.
  - Do not modify the component's hardcoded colors or fonts. They're frozen to match Prompting People's light-mode palette. The component should look like
   Prompting People wherever it's mounted — it shouldn't theme-shift to match the portfolio.

  Setup the component needs

  1. Three Google Fonts must be loaded: Geist, Geist Mono, and Newsreader (with italic). Use next/font/google in the root layout. Example:
  // app/layout.tsx
  import { Geist, Geist_Mono, Newsreader } from 'next/font/google'

  const geistSans = Geist({ subsets: ['latin'], variable: '--font-geist-sans' })
  const geistMono = Geist_Mono({ subsets: ['latin'], variable: '--font-geist-mono' })
  const newsreader = Newsreader({
    subsets: ['latin'],
    style: ['normal', 'italic'],
    variable: '--font-newsreader',
  })
  1. Then apply ${geistSans.variable} ${geistMono.variable} ${newsreader.variable} as classes on the <body>. The component's CSS references the fonts by
  name ('Geist', 'Geist Mono', 'Newsreader'), so as long as next/font makes them available globally on the page, the lookup resolves. Check whether these
  are already loaded — if they are, don't duplicate.
  2. Background context. The card uses a translucent surface (rgba(0,0,0,0.03)) which means it picks up whatever's behind it. For pixel-fidelity to the
  live Prompting People site, the immediate parent of <ResponseJournalSandbox /> should have a background of #F8F7F4 (the off-white the live site uses).
  If the work page already has that bg, you're fine. If it doesn't, wrap the mount point in a div with style={{ background: '#F8F7F4', padding: '32px',
  borderRadius: '16px' }} (tune padding/radius to taste — the goal is just to give the card the bg context it expects). Pick what fits the rest of the
  page; flag the choice in the change summary.

